tools_called.args:
{"query": "What are the available strategies for reducing the environmental impact of waste from salmon farms on the surrounding ecosystem?", "summary": "Several strategies are available for reducing environmental impact from salmon farm waste on surrounding ecosystems. Fallowing represents a proven approach where sediment community structure under Atlantic salmon cages became more similar to non-impacted sites over two fallowing cycles (Action 1027). A fallow period during fish farming shows that invertebrate community composition becomes similar to that occurring before fish were added, and abundances of pollution-indicator polychaete worms decrease, though communities remain different from sites without fish farms (Action 2191). 

Integrated aquaculture systems offer biological waste utilization where blue mussels absorbed waste from a salmon farm (Action 932), and enhanced algal growth occurred when placed adjacent to fish farms (Action 932). However, one study found no evidence that oysters and mussels were feeding on fish farm waste (Action 932). Greater growth of scallops was reported when grown next to fish farms (Action 932).

Several strategies are identified but lack research evidence including: improving fish food and pellets to reduce aquaculture waste production (Action 2192), locating aquaculture systems in areas with fast currents (Action 2188), using other bioremediation methods in aquaculture (Action 2197), mooring aquaculture cages so they move in response to changing current direction (Action 2190), and co-locating aquaculture systems with other activities to maximize marine space use (Action 2079).", "action_ids": ["1027","2191","932","2192","2188","2197","2190","2079"]}

